1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:05,140
Now let's talk about another model architecture that was designed

2

00:00:05,140  -->  00:00:10,600
specifically for processing sequential data like text or audio.

3

00:00:10,600  -->  00:00:17,860
This model architecture is called recurrent neural network or RNN for short.

4

00:00:17,860  -->  00:00:21,160
Previously, in all network architectures,

5

00:00:21,160  -->  00:00:25,620
we were looking into the data was going straight from

6

00:00:25,620  -->  00:00:34,210
inputs to outputs via one or multiple heating layers in between.

7

00:00:34,210  -->  00:00:38,110
Also, all input data was processed at once.

8

00:00:38,110  -->  00:00:44,240
We had to have all input data at once and pass it through the neural network.

9

00:00:44,240  -->  00:00:48,010
RNNs change both of these constraints.

10

00:00:48,010  -->  00:00:50,430
With the RNN architecture,

11

00:00:50,430  -->  00:00:55,830
we take the first input token and pass it through the network.

12

00:00:55,830  -->  00:00:59,470
Once the first token is processed by the network,

13

00:00:59,470  -->  00:01:05,290
we take the next token and pass it through the same network again.

14

00:01:05,290  -->  00:01:08,870
But now in addition to the new token,

15

00:01:08,870  -->  00:01:12,530
we also take the output of the hidden layer from

16

00:01:12,530  -->  00:01:17,010
the previous step and use it as an additional input,

17

00:01:17,010  -->  00:01:20,770
and we do the same thing on the next step.

18

00:01:20,770  -->  00:01:23,920
We keep the output of the hidden layer from

19

00:01:23,920  -->  00:01:29,510
the previous step and use it as an input together with the next token.

20

00:01:29,510  -->  00:01:35,300
The idea here is that the output of the hidden layer that is called the hidden state

21

00:01:35,300  -->  00:01:40,920
preserves some information about the previous inputs that we've already processed.

22

00:01:40,920  -->  00:01:43,740
When the model is processing the next token,

23

00:01:43,740  -->  00:01:49,060
it can access some information about tokens it saw before.

24

00:01:49,060  -->  00:01:52,520
For this to work, we also need to pass

25

00:01:52,520  -->  00:01:56,655
some initial empty state when processing the first token.

26

00:01:56,655  -->  00:02:00,400
RNNs is a great choice if we need to work with text,

27

00:02:00,400  -->  00:02:05,240
but they can also be used with other sequential data like audio,

28

00:02:05,240  -->  00:02:08,030
time series, et cetera.

29

00:02:08,030  -->  00:02:12,980
RNNs are commonly displayed in a compact form like this,

30

00:02:12,980  -->  00:02:16,580
where we have this recurrent connection.

31

00:02:16,580  -->  00:02:20,980
Now, here are some ways we can use RNNs.

32

00:02:20,980  -->  00:02:26,480
For classification purposes, we can ignore outputs from all steps,

33

00:02:26,480  -->  00:02:33,380
except the last one and use the last output to classify an input text,

34

00:02:33,380  -->  00:02:38,320
for example, to classify it into spam or non spam.

35

00:02:38,350  -->  00:02:41,180
We would pass an input text,

36

00:02:41,180  -->  00:02:44,200
token by token, [inaudible] this network,

37

00:02:44,200  -->  00:02:46,040
and on the final step,

38

00:02:46,040  -->  00:02:48,120
we should have some information about

39

00:02:48,120  -->  00:02:54,040
the previously processed words that we can use to make a classification decision.

40

00:02:54,040  -->  00:02:59,360
There are also other RNN variations such as one to many RNN,

41

00:02:59,360  -->  00:03:02,280
where we provide an initial input,

42

00:03:02,280  -->  00:03:06,615
and then the model generates multiple output tokens.

43

00:03:06,615  -->  00:03:11,675
This architecture is good for text generation or music generation.

44

00:03:11,675  -->  00:03:15,550
The other variation is called many to many RNNs,

45

00:03:15,550  -->  00:03:21,790
where we first read an input sequence that consists of multiple tokens,

46

00:03:21,790  -->  00:03:27,830
and then the model can generate multiple output tokens one by one.

47

00:03:27,830  -->  00:03:34,490
This approach can be used to translate text from one language to another.

48

00:03:34,490  -->  00:03:37,680
RNNs worked for many different tasks,

49

00:03:37,680  -->  00:03:40,390
however, they have a few issues.

50

00:03:40,390  -->  00:03:45,195
First of all, RNNs have difficulty accessing previous states.

51

00:03:45,195  -->  00:03:49,740
We have a single state that we need to update on every iteration,

52

00:03:49,740  -->  00:03:56,560
and the model will have issues retaining information from tokens it saw long time ago.

53

00:03:56,560  -->  00:04:01,260
The other issue with RNNs is called diminishing gradient.

54

00:04:01,260  -->  00:04:07,940
This happens when the gradient during training becomes too small in deep networks,

55

00:04:07,940  -->  00:04:11,360
which leads to slow training and the network

56

00:04:11,360  -->  00:04:15,440
can't capture dependencies over large time intervals.

57

00:04:15,440  -->  00:04:20,300
There were a number of improvements to the basic RNN architecture,

58

00:04:20,300  -->  00:04:24,850
such as LSTM or long short term memory,

59

00:04:24,850  -->  00:04:28,520
or GRU, which is gated recurrent unit.

60

00:04:28,520  -->  00:04:33,480
These architectures help with some of the drawbacks of classic cardan approach.

61

00:04:33,480  -->  00:04:37,620
However, the next breakthrough in NLP came from using

62

00:04:37,620  -->  00:04:43,320
the transformers architecture and the attention mechanism it uses.
